title: Speaker of Sejm Elections
subtitle: It is time to elect a new Speaker of Sejm...
view-if: year = 1928 and (month = 3) and speaker_election_seen = 0
frequency: 1000
max-visits: 1
new-page: true
on-arrival: bbwr_speaker_campaign = 0; other_support_pps = 0; speaker_election_seen = 1; pps_candidate = "Daszyński"; sn_candidate = "Zwierzyński"; minorities_candidate = "Leszczyński"; kpp_candidate = "Sypuła & Warski";
tags: event
go-to: election_algorithm
set-jump: speaker_election

@speaker_election

Few weeks after the elections newly elected Sejm gathered in Warsaw for one of its most anticipated sessions—the election of the Speaker. The atmosphere was charged. Fresh from a bitterly fought general election, the members of parliament (MPs) arrived knowing the day’s proceedings would define the political landscape for the coming term. [? if Q.in_bbwr_majority = 1 : The election of the Speaker of the Sejm should be a mere formality, given our majority in parliament. With Piłsudski’s camp holding the reins, the outcome appears predetermined, yet the opposition is sure to voice its discontent. While the process may be filled with posturing from various parties, our control ensures that we will shape this session's results.. ?][? if Q.in_bbwr_minority = 1 : We do not hold a majority in the Sejm, and the Speaker election will be anything but smooth. Victory will only be possible through deals, compromises, and, if necessary, direct threats to MPs. With Piłsudski's influence at stake, every vote counts, and the opposition will not give in easily. This is a battle we must win, but one that will require every bit of political maneuvering. ?]Piłsudski and his government, though claiming victory, faced stiff resistance from an emboldened opposition. Tensions were further heightened by the disqualification of numerous Communist candidates during the election, stoking discontent among the left-wing and minority representatives. Many expected disruption, especially from the Ukrainian and Communist MPs, who were still outraged by the government’s handling of the campaign.

- @pilsudski_arrival: Piłsudski’s Arrival

@pilsudski_arrival

As the MPs took their seats, Piłsudski arrived early. His presence cast a long shadow over the chamber, though he spoke little upon entering. Dressed in his military uniform, he moved quietly but purposefully, exchanging brief words with Jakub Bojko (former leader and political veteran of People's Movement, now member of BBWR), who had been surprisingly appointed Senior Speaker of the session. Bojko’s appointment raised eyebrows—it broke parliamentary tradition, as he wasn’t the eldest member present. Yet, like many things that day, it was a sign of Piłsudski’s influence. His authority was inescapable, and even in the opening minutes, it was clear the Marshal’s camp had set the tone for what was to follow.

- @pilsudski_speech: Piłsudski started his opening speech

@pilsudski_speech

Piłsudski began reading a message from the president, Ignacy Mościcki, when the chamber erupted into chaos. Ukrainian and Communist MPs, their frustrations simmering from months of repression, broke into loud protest. "Down with fascist government!" shouted one, while others followed with accusations: “Piłsudski persecutes Ukrainians!”.

Marshal Piłsudski, leaning heavily on the table with both hands, turns toward the shouting deputies and, in a firm, deliberate voice, declares, "Gentlemen, you will be thrown out of this chamber!" He repeats the warning twice, his words cutting through the noise, but the commotion refuses to die down.

The cries grew louder as opposition MPs joined the chorus, adding fuel to the fire. Their voices rang out: “This parliament is a farce!” “The elections were rigged!”

Piłsudski, mid-sentence, stopped and looked out over the shouting MPs. His face remained impassive, but the tension was palpable. The Sanation deputies sat in silence, watching the outburst unfold. Some hurled their own accusations at the protesters: “How much are you getting from Moscow for this?”

For a moment, Piłsudski paused, weighing his options. He could ignore the shouts and allow the chaos to subside, or he could make a statement. 

- @arrest_provocators: Piłsudski lost his patience

@arrest_provocators

His decision was swift. With a quiet nod, he gave the order to clear the chamber. Armed police units entered the Sejm, moving quickly to silence the disruption. Ukrainian and Communist MPs resisted, but force was met with force. In one dramatic scene, Ukrainian MP Baczyński was dragged out of the chamber by his legs, minister Sławoj-Składkowski overseeing the action. Seven MPs were arrested before the chamber fell silent once more.

Piłsudski returned to his reading as if nothing had happened. The message from the president was brief, but its delivery, under these conditions, was more telling than its content. He had demonstrated once again that disorder would not be tolerated under his watch.

- @swearing_in: It's time to move to swearing in of MPs

@swearing_in

With the chamber subdued, the next order of business began: the swearing-in of MPs. The opposition, still furious, argued that some of their colleagues had been unjustly imprisoned and should be allowed to take the oath. Bojko, unmoved by their protests, pressed forward with the proceedings. “You are not MPs until you’ve sworn in,” he declared, dismissing their appeals. One by one, members came forward to take their oath, the tension in the air still thick, but the process moved forward.

Suddenly, the uproar reignited, louder than before. Chaos filled the room once again, forcing Bojko to suspend the session. An hour passed since the break was called, and in the corridors, whispers and speculation swirled about the fate of the arrested deputies. Then, unexpectedly, they appeared—escorted by the Sejm's Guard, emerging from the shadows of their confinement. The deputies, surrounded by a crowd of supporters, were released from the guard’s custody, disappearing into the embrace of their colleagues.

The arrested MPs shared their stories, explaining how they had been taken by car to City Hall, each placed in separate cells. Not long after, the police brought them back to the Sejm, restoring their place in the proceedings.

Once the arrested deputies had returned and the break concluded, Bojko resumed the session and read aloud the oath. One by one, the deputies stood as their names were called, each declaring, “I swear.” The Ukrainian members, in a quiet act of defiance, responded with, “Prysiakhaju.”

As the swearing-in proceeded, Marshal Piłsudski departed for a Senate meeting. By 7:00 PM, he had left for Belweder, leaving behind a chamber still buzzing with tension and the weight of what was yet to come.

- @speaker_election_start: It's finally time to elected Sejm's Speaker

Finally, the moment everyone had been waiting for arrived: the election of the Speaker. Each faction had put forth its candidate. Rulling camp had two clear options, reflecting the internal divisions within their ranks. The Colonels' faction, fiercely loyal to Piłsudski, leaned toward nominating Kazimierz Świtalski, a close and unwavering supporter of the Marshal. However, Świtalski's candidacy presented a challenge—his loyalty to Piłsudski was unquestioned, but his ability to garner support from other parties seemed unlikely without significant effort and persuasion.

On the other hand, there was Kazimierz Bartel, a former Prime Minister and current Deputy Prime Minister, representing the more liberal wing of the Sanation movement. Bartel was a pragmatic choice, more palatable to the left-wing and minority factions. However, his nomination carried risks as well. His ties to the liberal side of the party could alienate the more conservative elements of Sanation, who might see this as a concession to the opposition rather than a victory.

Meanwhile, the Polish Socialist Party (PPS) backed the respected Ignacy Daszyński, a figure well-known for his leadership and integrity. PPS already managed to convince other left-wing parties (SCh and PSL-W) for their candidate. The National Democrats (ZLN), determined to counter the government’s influence, nominated Aleksander Zwierzyński. Centre-right parties (PSCHD, NPR, PSL-P) did not pick their own candidate and it is expected they wont vote at all. The Ukrainian bloc supported Jan Leszczyński, hoping to secure a candidate sympathetic to minority rights. Even the Communists, weakened by the day’s arrests, proposed Konstanty Sypuła and Adolf Warski, though it was clear their chances were slim.

The decision now lay in Sanation’s hands. Should they rally behind the loyal Świtalski and risk alienating potential allies, or choose the more moderate Bartel and risk internal division? The next move would shape the future of the Sejm.

[? if pps_relation >= 50 : Another possibilty is an united front with left wing parties, either to support Daszyński or our own candidate. ?]

